  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Education in Emergencies for Children Displaced by Armed Conflict in Faryab, Kunduz, Nangarhar, and Uruzgan</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The Norwegian Refugee Council (NRC) and Norwegian Afghanistan Committee (NAC) will directly implement an Education in Emergencies response to protect boys and girls displaced internally by armed conflict in four under-served provinces afflicted by severe insecurity and significant levels of displacement, which are prioritized in this allocation strategy: Nangarhar, Faryab, Kunduz, and Uruzgan. 

Operating in 12 districts across the four provinces, the project intends to directly assist 24,145 conflict-affected IDPs, returnees and host community members (704 men, 708 women, 11,139 boys, 11,594 girls) in the following hard-to-reach districts: Kunduz (Emam Sahib, AliAbad, Qala-e-Zal, Kunduz) Faryab (Qaisar, Pashtunkot, Almar, Shirintagab, Khwajasabzposh and Dawlatabad), Nangarhar (Khogyani-Chamtala), and Uruzgan (Tirin Kot). Importantly, the action mounts a large-scale EiE response to the thousands of children displaced by Islamic State-aligned groups in Nangarhar, and also opens the first EiE interventions for many years in the conflict-afflicted, hard-to-reach province of Uruzgan.

The action will be conducted in partnership between NAC and NRC, with the former operating in three of the aforementioned districts (all in Faryab), and NRC in the remaining nine districts (in Faryab, Nangarhar and Uruzgan). The partnership enables cross-fertilisation of relevant expertise, specifically regarding NAC&#x2019;s work in building a more inclusive education system through high-quality teacher training of EiE teaching staff, and through NRC&#x2019;s experience in delivering high quality education. The partnership also ensures a broader reach within Faryab Province

In this project, NRC is partnering with Norwegian Afghanistan Committee (NAC) on teacher training. NAC will develop teacher training materials and train 230 teachers, establish 30 EiE classes enrolling 1,800 children, recruit and train 12 community mobilisers and support 15 school shuras. NAC&apos;s total budget under this action is $319,080</narrative>
  </description>
